window.MM['oph_p2_lacrimal']=[
  {q:"A 45-year-old woman presents with painful swelling at the medial canthus below the medial canthal tendon with epiphora. Pressure on the swelling produces mucopurulent regurgitation through the punctum. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Acute dacryocystitis","Dacryocele","Medial canthal cyst","Orbital cellulitis","Angular conjunctivitis"],a:0,e:"Acute dacryocystitis presents with painful erythematous swelling below the medial canthal tendon from infected nasolacrimal sac. Mucopurulent regurgitation on pressure through the punctum confirms lacrimal sac involvement.<br><br>Intravenous antibiotics are required for severe cases. Surgical DCR is planned after resolution of the acute infection.<br><br>Dacryocele (B) is a tense non-tender swelling. Medial canthal cyst (C) is above the medial canthal tendon. Orbital cellulitis (D) causes proptosis and restricted motility. Angular conjunctivitis (E) causes medial conjunctival inflammation without lacrimal sac swelling.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old woman presents with chronic watering eye and medial canthal swelling for two years. She has had three episodes of acute dacryocystitis. What is the definitive surgical treatment?",o:["Dacryocystorhinostomy","Lacrimal sac massage","Silicone tube intubation","Punctal dilation alone","Topical antibiotic drops"],a:0,e:"Dacryocystorhinostomy creates a new drainage channel from the lacrimal sac directly into the nasal cavity bypassing the obstructed nasolacrimal duct. It is the definitive treatment for NLD obstruction with chronic dacryocystitis.<br><br>External DCR has a success rate exceeding 90%. Endonasal DCR achieves equivalent results without a skin incision. Mitomycin C reduces fibrosis and improves surgical success rates.<br><br>Lacrimal sac massage (B) is for congenital NLD obstruction in infants. Silicone tube intubation (C) is for partial obstruction. Punctal dilation alone (D) treats punctal stenosis not NLD obstruction. Topical antibiotics (E) treat infection not the underlying obstruction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 2-week-old neonate presents with a bluish medial canthal swelling present since birth. It is compressible and transilluminates. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Acute dacryocystitis","Haemangioma of the medial canthus","Dacryocystocele","Dermoid cyst medial canthus","Encephalocele"],a:2,e:"Dacryocystocele is a congenital distension of the lacrimal sac from amniotic fluid or mucus trapped between the valve of Rosenmuller superiorly and the valve of Hasner inferiorly. It appears as a bluish compressible transilluminant medial canthal swelling at birth.<br><br>Probing and massage resolve most cases. Intranasal marsupialization of the associated intranasal cyst is required when there is nasal obstruction causing respiratory distress.<br><br>Acute dacryocystitis (A) is painful and erythematous. Haemangioma (B) appears in the first weeks and is not present from birth. Dermoid cyst (D) is firm and superotemporal. Encephalocele (E) is pulsatile and increases with crying.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old man presents with acute dacryocystitis. After resolution with antibiotics he undergoes DCR. Intraoperatively the surgeon creates an osteotomy between the lacrimal sac and the nasal cavity. Which bone is removed to create the osteotomy in external DCR?",o:["Lacrimal bone and frontal process of the maxilla","Palatine bone","Lacrimal bone","Ethmoid bone","Nasal bone"],a:0,e:"In external DCR, the osteotomy is made by removing the lacrimal bone posteriorly and the frontal process of the maxilla anteriorly to create a direct communication between the lacrimal sac fossa and the nasal cavity.<br><br>The osteotomy should measure approximately 15 to 20 mm to prevent fibrotic closure. Anterior and posterior flaps of the lacrimal sac mucosa and nasal mucosa are anastomosed to maintain patency.<br><br>Ethmoid bone (D) is not removed in standard external DCR. Palatine bone (B) is not at the lacrimal fossa. Lacrimal bone alone (C) is incomplete. Nasal bone (E) is not part of the lacrimal fossa anatomy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old presents with acute dacryocystitis and a pointing abscess at the medial canthus. What is the immediate management?",o:["Incision and drainage then","DCR surgery immediately","Topical antibiotics only","Warm compresses only","Intravenous antibiotics alone"],a:0,e:"A pointing lacrimal abscess requires immediate incision and drainage to release the pus followed by systemic antibiotics. Incision is made at the point of maximum fluctuation avoiding the medial canthal tendon.<br><br>DCR is planned electively after complete resolution of infection. Immediate DCR through infected tissue carries risks of fistula formation and surgical failure.<br><br>Intravenous antibiotics alone (E) are insufficient for a fluctuant abscess. Immediate DCR (B) through infected tissue risks failure. Topical antibiotics (C) are inadequate. Warm compresses alone (D) do not drain an established abscess.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old woman with chronic dacryocystitis develops a lacrimal fistula draining onto the skin below the medial canthus. What is the most likely cause?",o:["Spontaneous fistula from recurrent abscesses","Trauma to the medial canthus","Post-surgical fistula from failed DCR","Congenital lacrimal fistula present","Malignancy of the lacrimal sac"],a:0,e:"Recurrent acute dacryocystitis abscesses that point and drain spontaneously through the skin create a lacrimal cutaneous fistula below the medial canthal tendon. The chronic fistula drains tears and mucus permanently.<br><br>DCR combined with fistula excision is the definitive treatment. The fistula tract must be completely excised to prevent recurrence as residual epithelialised tract leads to persistent drainage.<br><br>Trauma (B) typically causes fistula above the medial canthal tendon. Failed DCR (C) causes rhinostomy closure not cutaneous fistula. Congenital fistula (D) is present from birth superomedially. Lacrimal sac malignancy (E) causes bloodstained discharge.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old presents with acute dacryocystitis. The most common organism causing acute dacryocystitis in adults is?",o:["Staphylococcus aureus","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Streptococcus viridans","Haemophilus influenzae","Candida albicans"],a:0,e:"Staphylococcus aureus is the most common causative organism in acute dacryocystitis followed by Streptococcus pneumoniae. In chronic dacryocystitis Staphylococcus epidermidis and Pseudomonas are more common.<br><br>Gram stain and culture of the regurgitated material guide antibiotic selection. Empirical intravenous flucloxacillin or co-amoxiclav covers the most likely organisms pending culture results.<br><br>Pseudomonas (B) is more common in chronic dacryocystitis. Streptococcus viridans (C) is less commonly the primary pathogen. Haemophilus influenzae (D) is more common in children. Candida (E) causes fungal dacryocystitis in immunocompromised patients.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old woman develops recurrent ipsilateral conjunctivitis and epiphora. Syringing of the nasolacrimal duct shows reflux of mucopurulent material. What does this finding indicate?",o:["Canalicular obstruction","Nasolacrimal duct obstruction with secondary lacrimal sac infection","Punctal stenosis only","Common canalicular obstruction","Functional lacrimal drainage failure"],a:1,e:"Reflux of mucopurulent material on NLD syringing confirms a distended infected lacrimal sac from NLD obstruction. The sac acts as a reservoir for bacteria causing recurrent conjunctivitis and epiphora.<br><br>A distended infected sac carries a risk of acute dacryocystitis and corneal ulcer from contamination of the ocular surface. DCR is the definitive treatment eliminating the mucocele and the NLD obstruction.<br><br>Canalicular obstruction (A) produces clear fluid regurgitation through the same canaliculus. Punctal stenosis (C) prevents fluid entry. Common canalicular obstruction (D) shows regurgitation through the opposite canaliculus. Functional failure (E) shows normal syringing.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 50-year-old presents with bloodstained discharge from the medial canthus and a firm irregular medial canthal mass. Dacryocystography shows an irregular filling defect in the lacrimal sac. What must be excluded?",o:["Acute dacryocystitis","Lacrimal sac mucocele","Lacrimal sac malignancy","Rhinoscleroma","Sarcoidosis of the lacrimal sac"],a:2,e:"Bloodstained discharge, a firm mass above the medial canthal tendon, and irregular filling defect on dacryocystography are the classic warning signs of lacrimal sac malignancy. Biopsy is mandatory before any surgical intervention.<br><br>Squamous cell carcinoma and transitional cell carcinoma are the most common lacrimal sac malignancies. DCR is absolutely contraindicated before malignancy is excluded as it spreads tumour.<br><br>Acute dacryocystitis (A) is painful without bloodstained discharge. Mucocele (B) is smooth and compressible. Rhinoscleroma (D) is a specific granulomatous infection. Sarcoidosis (E) causes bilateral lacrimal system involvement without bloodstained discharge.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 3-year-old child presents with recurrent mucopurulent discharge from the left eye since birth. The right eye is normal. Syringing shows reflux through the opposite punctum. What is the first-line management?",o:["External DCR surgery immediately","Topical antibiotics for three months","Silicone tube intubation","Probing of the nasolacrimal duct","Endonasal DCR surgery"],a:3,e:"NLD probing is the first-line treatment for congenital NLD obstruction persisting beyond one year of age. The probe is passed through the canaliculus and lacrimal sac to perforate the membranous obstruction at the valve of Hasner, restoring normal drainage.<br><br>Success rate of probing exceeds 90% when performed before two years. Repeated probing or silicone tube intubation is offered if initial probing fails.<br><br>External DCR (A) and endonasal DCR (E) are reserved for failed probing. Topical antibiotics (B) manage secondary infection but do not clear the obstruction. Silicone tube intubation (C) follows failed probing.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old undergoes external DCR. Which flap anastomosis is most critical for surgical success?",o:["Posterior flaps only","Anterior flaps only","Neither flap anastomosis affects success","Combined anterior and posterior flap anastomosis equally","Posterior flap is more important than anterior"],a:4,e:"The posterior flap anastomosis between the posterior lacrimal sac mucosal flap and the posterior nasal mucosal flap is the most important anastomosis for DCR success. It creates the primary drainage pathway and must be watertight.<br><br>If posterior flaps cannot be sutured, anterior flaps alone may suffice but success rates are lower. Silicone tubes stent the new rhinostomy during healing.<br><br>Posterior flaps only (A) is incomplete. Anterior flaps only (B) is the least successful combination. Neither flap mattering (C) is incorrect. Combined equally (D) is incorrect as the posterior flap is the critical component.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old woman is treated for acute dacryocystitis. She has a penicillin allergy. What is the most appropriate antibiotic?",o:["Flucloxacillin intravenously","Co-amoxiclav intravenously","Ciprofloxacin orally","Clarithromycin orally","Metronidazole alone"],a:3,e:"In penicillin-allergic patients with acute dacryocystitis, clarithromycin or erythromycin provides cover for Staphylococcus aureus and Streptococcus pneumoniae, the most common causative organisms, without causing allergic reaction.<br><br>Clindamycin is an alternative with excellent gram-positive coverage. Intravenous vancomycin is used for severe penicillin-allergic cases requiring hospital admission.<br><br>Flucloxacillin (A) and co-amoxiclav (B) are penicillin-based and contraindicated. Ciprofloxacin (C) has poor gram-positive coverage for Staphylococcus aureus. Metronidazole alone (E) treats anaerobes only and is insufficient monotherapy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 6-week-old infant has mucopurulent discharge and medial canthal swelling since birth. The mother is taught lacrimal sac massage. What is the correct technique?",o:["Firm downward pressure on the lacrimal sac","Circular massage of the periorbital area","Pressure above the medial canthal tendon","Gentle nasal bridge massage only","Pressure at the inner canthus during"],a:0,e:"Crigler massage involves placing the index finger over the lacrimal sac below the medial canthal tendon and applying firm downward pressure. The resulting hydrostatic pressure within the sac forces against the membranous obstruction at the valve of Hasner.<br><br>Performed five to ten times, four to six times daily, Crigler massage resolves congenital NLD obstruction in up to 90% of cases within the first year.<br><br>Pressure above the tendon (C) empties the sac upward not downward. Circular massage (B) has no hydrostatic effect. Nasal bridge massage (D) is ineffective. Pressure during feeding (E) is not a recognised technique.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 48-year-old woman presents with dacryocystitis secondary to Wegener granulomatosis. Which specific treatment is required in addition to lacrimal drainage surgery?",o:["Topical antifungal therapy","Systemic immunosuppression with cyclophosphamide and steroids","Orbital radiotherapy","Topical steroid drops only","Intranasal corticosteroid spray"],a:1,e:"Granulomatosis with polyangiitis causes granulomatous infiltration of the nasolacrimal system causing dacryocystitis and NLD obstruction. DCR alone is insufficient; systemic cyclophosphamide and prednisolone treat the underlying vasculitis.<br><br>Lacrimal drainage surgery has higher failure rates in GPA due to ongoing granulomatous inflammation. Systemic disease control must precede or accompany surgical intervention for optimal outcomes.<br><br>Topical antifungal (A) treats fungal dacryocystitis not GPA. Orbital radiotherapy (C) is not indicated. Topical steroids (D) are insufficient for systemic vasculitis. Intranasal steroids (E) do not treat granulomatous NLD disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old presents with epiphora and recurrent conjunctivitis. On lacrimal syringing, clear fluid passes easily but refluxes through the same punctum. Where is the obstruction?",o:["Nasolacrimal duct","Common canaliculus","Upper canaliculus only","Lower canaliculus","Punctum"],a:3,e:"Reflux of clear fluid through the same canaliculus on syringing indicates obstruction within that canaliculus. Clear fluid indicates no lacrimal sac infection. The obstruction is within the lower canaliculus proximal to the common canaliculus.<br><br>Canalicular obstruction can be treated with canaliculotomy and placement of a silicone tube. Causes include herpes simplex infection, topical medication toxicity including pilocarpine, and previous trauma.<br><br>Nasolacrimal duct obstruction (A) produces mucopurulent reflux through the opposite punctum. Common canalicular obstruction (B) produces clear fluid through the opposite canaliculus. Upper canaliculus (C) would show reflux on upper punctum syringing. Punctal stenosis (E) prevents probe entry.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old man with chronic dacryocystitis is found to have actinomyces on culture. What is the specific treatment for actinomyces dacryocystitis?",o:["Intravenous fluconazole","Topical natamycin","Oral metronidazole","Prolonged intravenous penicillin","Surgical curettage alone"],a:3,e:"Actinomyces israelii causes chronic granulomatous dacryocystitis characterised by sulphur granules in the discharge. Treatment requires prolonged high-dose intravenous penicillin for four to six weeks followed by oral amoxicillin.<br><br>Canaliculotomy to remove the inspissated concretions containing actinomyces colonies combined with antibiotic therapy achieves the best outcomes.<br><br>Intravenous fluconazole (A) treats fungal infections. Topical natamycin (B) is for fungal keratitis. Oral metronidazole (C) treats anaerobic infections but is insufficient for actinomyces. Surgical curettage alone (E) without antibiotics results in recurrence.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A neonate presents two days after birth with bilateral mucopurulent conjunctivitis and medial canthal swelling. The discharge is copious. Gram stain shows gram-negative intracellular diplococci. What is the cause?",o:["Chlamydial ophthalmia neonatorum","Chemical conjunctivitis from silver nitrate","Staphylococcal dacryocystitis","Herpes simplex neonatal infection","Gonococcal ophthalmia with secondary"],a:4,e:"Gonococcal ophthalmia neonatorum presents within 2 to 5 days of birth with hyperacute bilateral purulent discharge. Gram-negative intracellular diplococci confirm Neisseria gonorrhoeae. Secondary dacryocystitis occurs from infection spreading into the nasolacrimal sac.<br><br>Systemic ceftriaxone is mandatory due to beta-lactamase resistance. Topical saline irrigation reduces the bacterial load. Neonatal screening of the mother is essential.<br><br>Chlamydial ophthalmia (A) presents at 5 to 14 days. Chemical conjunctivitis (B) is bilateral but resolves within 24 hours without organisms. Staphylococcal dacryocystitis (C) is not hyperacute. Herpes simplex (D) causes vesicular skin lesions.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old presents with recurrent acute dacryocystitis. On examination she has a deviated nasal septum and inferior turbinate hypertrophy. How does this affect DCR surgical planning?",o:["Nasal anatomy has no relevance to DCR success","Endonasal DCR with simultaneous septoplasty and turbinate reduction","External DCR bypasses nasal anatomy entirely","Topical decongestants alone resolve the obstruction","DCR should be postponed indefinitely"],a:1,e:"Significant nasal pathology including deviated septum and turbinate hypertrophy obstructs the nasal space required for endonasal DCR and impairs postoperative drainage. Simultaneous septoplasty and turbinate reduction during endonasal DCR optimises the nasal airway and drainage pathway.<br><br>ENT collaboration improves surgical planning. External DCR may also be performed but the nasal component still opens into the obstructed nasal cavity.<br><br>Nasal anatomy irrelevant (A) is incorrect. External DCR bypassing anatomy (C) is incorrect as the ostium opens into the nasal cavity. Topical decongestants (D) do not resolve NLD obstruction. Indefinite postponement (E) is inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old man with recurrent dacryocystitis is found to have sarcoidosis with granulomatous NLD obstruction. What is the most likely pathological mechanism?",o:["Primary NLD fibrosis from ageing","Dacryolith formation blocking the NLD","Pressure from enlarged infraorbital lymph nodes","Granulomatous infiltration of the NLD mucosa causing luminal obstruction","Secondary"],a:3,e:"Sarcoidosis causes non-caseating granulomatous infiltration of the nasolacrimal duct mucosa and lacrimal sac wall causing epiphora and dacryocystitis. Histology of the excised sac confirms non-caseating granulomas confirming the diagnosis.<br><br>Systemic steroids reduce lacrimal system granulomas. DCR is required for established obstruction. Bilateral involvement is characteristic of sarcoid lacrimal system disease.<br><br>Primary NLD fibrosis from ageing (A) is age-related involutional obstruction. Dacryolith (B) causes partial obstruction visible on dacryocystography. Infraorbital lymph node pressure (C) is not the mechanism. Secondary infection scarring (E) is a consequence not the cause in sarcoidosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old man presents with unilateral epiphora after long-term topical pilocarpine for glaucoma. What is the mechanism of pilocarpine-induced lacrimal obstruction?",o:["Pilocarpine increases tear production overwhelming drainage","Pilocarpine constricts the pupil blocking punctal drainage","Chronic pilocarpine causes punctal and canalicular fibrosis","Pilocarpine causes lacrimal gland hypertrophy","Pilocarpine increases nasal"],a:2,e:"Chronic topical pilocarpine causes direct chemical toxicity to the lacrimal drainage epithelium causing progressive punctal, canalicular, and NLD fibrosis. This is a well-recognised iatrogenic cause of acquired lacrimal obstruction with long-term use.<br><br>Switching to alternative glaucoma medications and DCR surgery address the obstruction. Other causative topical drops include idoxuridine and echothiophate iodide with chronic use.<br><br>Increased tear production (A) causes functional not obstructive epiphora. Pupil constriction (B) has no relationship to punctal drainage. Lacrimal gland hypertrophy (D) does not occur with pilocarpine. Nasal secretion increase (E) is not the mechanism.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old woman presents with medial canthal swelling and mucopurulent discharge. Dacryocystography shows a large filling defect within the lacrimal sac with irregular walls. What should the surgeon do before performing DCR?",o:["Biopsy the lacrimal sac to exclude malignancy","Perform lacrimal sac massage and antibiotics first","Proceed directly to DCR without further investigation","Perform endonasal DCR under local anaesthetic","Try nasolacrimal duct probing first"],a:0,e:"An irregular filling defect within the lacrimal sac on dacryocystography raises strong suspicion of lacrimal sac malignancy. Biopsy is mandatory before DCR as performing DCR through a malignant sac spreads tumour cells along the surgical tract.<br><br>CT scan delineates bony involvement. MRI assesses soft tissue extent. Squamous cell carcinoma is the most common primary lacrimal sac malignancy requiring radical excision not DCR.<br><br>Proceeding directly to DCR (C) risks spreading malignancy. Massage and antibiotics (B) are inappropriate for a suspected malignant lesion. Endonasal DCR (D) is contraindicated. Probing (E) is inappropriate for adults with suspected malignancy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old woman with acute dacryocystitis asks about the risk of endophthalmitis. In which specific clinical scenario does dacryocystitis pose the highest risk of endophthalmitis?",o:["During topical antibiotic treatment","After probing in children","During cataract surgery in a patient with active dacryocystitis","After silicone tube removal","During endonasal DCR"],a:2,e:"Active dacryocystitis is a contraindication to cataract surgery because the infected nasolacrimal sac provides a reservoir of organisms adjacent to the surgical wound site. Intraocular inoculation during surgery causes devastating acute endophthalmitis.<br><br>DCR must be performed and confirmed successful before any intraocular surgery is undertaken. Cataract surgery in an eye with documented active dacryocystitis has a dramatically elevated risk of postoperative endophthalmitis.<br><br>Topical antibiotic treatment (A) is safe. Probing in children (B) carries minimal endophthalmitis risk. After silicone tube removal (D) the obstruction is resolved. During endonasal DCR (E) is not an endophthalmitis risk setting.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 28-year-old woman develops acute dacryocystitis during pregnancy. What is the most appropriate antibiotic?",o:["Ciprofloxacin intravenously","Tetracycline orally","Amoxicillin-clavulanate orally","Doxycycline orally","Metronidazole"],a:2,e:"Amoxicillin-clavulanate is safe in pregnancy and provides broad-spectrum coverage for Staphylococcus aureus, Streptococcus, and gram-negative organisms commonly causing dacryocystitis. DCR surgery is deferred until after delivery unless the infection becomes severe.<br><br>Penicillin-based antibiotics are category B in pregnancy. Surgical intervention is reserved for abscess formation or failure of medical treatment posing greater risk than intervention.<br><br>Ciprofloxacin (A) is avoided in pregnancy due to cartilage effects. Tetracycline (B) and doxycycline (D) are contraindicated in pregnancy. Metronidazole alone (E) is insufficient for staphylococcal dacryocystitis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old man underwent external DCR six months ago. He still has persistent epiphora. On examination the rhinostomy is patent on syringing but he still has watering. What is the most likely cause?",o:["Surgical failure with rhinostomy closure","Lacrimal pump failure from orbicularis weakness","Recurrent NLD obstruction","Punctal eversion causing tear overflow","Corneal surface disease causing reflex"],a:1,e:"Functional epiphora after patent DCR results from lacrimal pump failure. The orbicularis oculi contracts with each blink creating a negative pressure that pumps tears into the canaliculi. Facial nerve weakness or orbicularis laxity impairs this mechanism causing epiphora despite a patent rhinostomy.<br><br>Medial canthal tendon laxity allows the punctum to evert away from the tear lake. Treatment addresses the specific anatomical cause of pump failure.<br><br>Rhinostomy closure (A) would show failure to irrigate. Recurrent NLD obstruction (C) is excluded by patent syringing. Punctal eversion (D) is a separate cause. Corneal surface disease (E) causes reflex tearing not pump failure.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old presents with chronic dacryocystitis from a dacryolith. What is a dacryolith and how is it managed?",o:["A calcified tumour treated by lacrimal sac excision","Calcium deposits on the external sac wall","Fungal concretion treated with antifungals only","Lacrimal sac polyp causing intermittent obstruction","Calcified concretion within the sac treated by DCR"],a:4,e:"Dacryoliths are calcified concretions within the lacrimal sac formed from desquamated epithelial cells, mucin, and mineral deposits. They cause intermittent or complete NLD obstruction and dacryocystitis. DCR with removal of the dacryolith restores drainage.<br><br>Dacryocystography shows a filling defect within the sac corresponding to the dacryolith. They are typically small, hard, and white-yellow on surgical removal.<br><br>Calcified tumour (A) is lacrimal sac malignancy. Calcium on external wall (B) is not a dacryolith. Fungal concretion (C) is actinomycosis treated differently. Lacrimal sac polyp (D) is a different pathology entirely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old woman with trachoma presents with bilateral epiphora and recurrent dacryocystitis. What is the mechanism of NLD obstruction in trachoma?",o:["Viral destruction of the lacrimal sac epithelium","Chlamydial granulomatous infiltration of the NLD causing fibrosis","Secondary bacterial infection causing permanent scarring only","Tarsal scarring causing punctal ectropion","Pannus growth blocking the puncta"],a:1,e:"Chlamydia trachomatis causes chronic granulomatous inflammation throughout the lacrimal drainage system. Fibrosis of the nasolacrimal duct and lacrimal sac results in permanent obstruction causing epiphora and recurrent dacryocystitis.<br><br>DCR is the treatment but success rates are lower than in other causes due to the diffuse fibrotic process. Systemic azithromycin or doxycycline treats active Chlamydia infection.<br><br>Viral destruction (A) is not the trachoma mechanism. Secondary bacterial infection (C) occurs but is not the primary mechanism. Tarsal scarring causes trichiasis and entropion (D) not NLD obstruction specifically. Pannus (E) grows over the cornea not the puncta.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old woman undergoes external DCR. The surgeon inadvertently enters the anterior ethmoidal air cells instead of the nasal cavity. How is this identified intraoperatively?",o:["Immediate profuse haemorrhage from ethmoidal arteries","Absence of nasal endoscopic light confirming ethmoidal entry","CSF leak from inadvertent skull base entry","Loss of olfaction from olfactory nerve injury","Orbital fat prolapse into the surgical field"],a:1,e:"The nasal cavity is confirmed intraoperatively by transillumination or direct visualisation of the light from a nasal endoscope through the osteotomy. If the surgeon has entered the anterior ethmoidal cells, the nasal endoscope light is absent confirming incorrect osteotomy position.<br><br>The osteotomy must be repositioned anteriorly and inferiorly to enter the true nasal cavity. The ethmoidal air cells must be carefully distinguished from the nasal space.<br><br>Profuse haemorrhage (A) indicates anterior ethmoidal artery damage not entry into cells. CSF leak (C) indicates skull base entry superiorly. Olfactory nerve injury (D) is not associated with ethmoidal entry. Orbital fat prolapse (E) indicates orbital periosteum injury.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old woman with acute dacryocystitis also has a corneal ulcer in the same eye. What is the relationship between dacryocystitis and corneal ulcer?",o:["Both conditions are entirely coincidental","The corneal ulcer causes lacrimal drainage impairment","Topical antibiotics cause both conditions simultaneously","The infected lacrimal sac contaminates the ocular surface causing corneal ulcer","The corneal ulcer is from dry"],a:3,e:"The infected lacrimal sac acts as a bacterial reservoir continuously contaminating the ocular surface with organisms. In the presence of corneal epithelial compromise or trauma, this causes bacterial corneal ulcer, classically called the hypopyon ulcer of dacryocystitis.<br><br>This is a classic and frequently examined clinical association. Treating the corneal ulcer requires simultaneous drainage of the infected sac to eliminate the source of contamination.<br><br>Both conditions coincidental (A) is incorrect. Corneal ulcer causing lacrimal impairment (B) is the reverse relationship. Topical antibiotics causing both (C) is incorrect. Dry eye from blockage (E) causes punctate epitheliopathy not a bacterial corneal ulcer.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old man presents with a firm painless swelling above the medial canthal tendon. It is non-compressible and not associated with epiphora. CT shows a soft tissue mass arising from the lacrimal sac extending superiorly. What is the most important differential?",o:["Medial canthal cyst","Dacryocystocele in an adult","Lacrimal sac tumour","Acute dacryocystitis","Orbital cellulitis medially"],a:2,e:"A firm non-compressible mass above the medial canthal tendon without epiphora or regurgitation raises high suspicion for lacrimal sac malignancy. Dacryocystitis swelling is typically below the medial canthal tendon and compressible.<br><br>Biopsy and CT staging are mandatory. Squamous cell carcinoma is most common. Treatment requires radical excision with wide margins and postoperative radiotherapy.<br><br>Medial canthal cyst (A) is soft and compressible. Adult dacryocystocele (B) is compressible with epiphora. Acute dacryocystitis (D) is painful and below the medial canthal tendon. Orbital cellulitis (E) causes proptosis and restricted motility.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old woman undergoes endonasal DCR. What is the primary advantage of endonasal over external DCR?",o:["No external skin incision avoiding scarring","Better haemostasis during surgery","Higher success rate than external DCR","Easier surgical learning curve","No need for general anaesthesia"],a:0,e:"Endonasal DCR avoids the external skin incision and scar of external DCR, preserving the lacrimal pump mechanism and reducing postoperative swelling. Cosmesis is the primary advantage cited by patients.<br><br>Success rates of endonasal and external DCR are equivalent at approximately 85 to 90% in experienced hands. Endonasal DCR allows simultaneous nasal pathology correction.<br><br>Higher success rate (C) is not the advantage as rates are equivalent. Better haemostasis (B) is not consistent. Easier learning curve (D) is the opposite as endonasal has a steeper curve. General anaesthesia is often still used (E).<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 6-week-old infant has unilateral watering and discharge since birth. The right eye is normal. Conservative management with massage has failed. At what age is probing recommended?",o:["Immediately at six weeks of age","After three months of age if massage fails","Only after two years if all other treatments fail","At six to twelve months of age if conservative management fails","Probing"],a:3,e:"NLD probing is recommended at six to twelve months of age if conservative Crigler massage fails to resolve congenital NLD obstruction. The majority resolve spontaneously by one year making early probing unnecessary in most cases.<br><br>Success rates of probing decline after two years of age due to progressive membrane fibrosis. Probing under general anaesthesia is the standard approach with an over 90% success rate.<br><br>Immediate probing at six weeks (A) is premature. After three months (B) is too early. After two years (C) has lower success rates. Never before one year (E) is too restrictive as probing is recommended from six months if needed.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 25-year-old woman presents with bilateral NLD obstruction after chemotherapy with docetaxel. What is the mechanism of docetaxel-induced NLD obstruction?",o:["Direct lacrimal gland toxicity reducing tears","Canalicular fibrosis from docetaxel secreted in tears","Antifibrinolytic lacrimal sac thrombosis","Hypersecretion overwhelming the drainage system","Conjunctival goblet cell loss causing mucus plugging"],a:1,e:"Docetaxel is secreted in tears at high concentrations causing direct chemical toxicity to the canalicular and NLD mucosa. Progressive inflammation and fibrosis lead to canalicular stenosis and NLD obstruction causing epiphora.<br><br>Silicone tube intubation during chemotherapy may prevent obstruction. Punctal dilation, probing, and DCR treat established obstruction. Bilateral presentation is characteristic of systemic drug-induced obstruction.<br><br>Direct lacrimal gland toxicity (A) causes dry eye not obstruction. Antifibrinolytic thrombosis (C) is not the mechanism. Hypersecretion (D) causes functional epiphora. Goblet cell loss (E) causes dry eye not luminal obstruction.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old man with bilateral NLD obstruction and chronic dacryocystitis is planned for bilateral DCR. What is the recommendation regarding timing of bilateral DCR?",o:["Bilateral simultaneous DCR in one session","Staged bilateral DCR with at least six weeks between procedures","Right DCR then left DCR on the same day","Bilateral DCR with simultaneous cataract surgery","Bilateral simultaneous DCR only in children"],a:1,e:"Staged bilateral DCR with at least six weeks between operations is recommended because simultaneous bilateral nasal surgery risks bilateral nasal packing complications and airway compromise. Staged procedures allow assessment of the first side before proceeding.<br><br>In exceptional cases bilateral simultaneous endonasal DCR may be performed under general anaesthesia with experienced surgical and anaesthetic teams, but this remains non-standard practice.<br><br>Bilateral simultaneous DCR in adults (A) risks bilateral nasal airway compromise. Same-day surgery (C) is uncomfortable and risky. Simultaneous cataract surgery (D) is inappropriate in an infected setting. Bilateral simultaneous DCR only in children (E) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 50-year-old woman presents with epiphora after radiation therapy to the head and neck for nasopharyngeal carcinoma three years ago. NLD syringing shows complete obstruction. What is the cause?",o:["Radiation-induced lacrimal gland destruction causing dry eye","Recurrent nasopharyngeal carcinoma causing NLD compression","Chemotherapy-induced canalicular fibrosis","Radiation-induced NLD mucosal fibrosis and stenosis","Radiation-induced conjunctival scarring"],a:3,e:"Radiation therapy causes direct DNA damage to rapidly dividing NLD mucosal cells followed by fibrosis causing progressive stenosis and complete obstruction. This occurs months to years after radiation exposure to the head and neck.<br><br>DCR is technically more challenging in irradiated tissue due to poor wound healing and fibrosis. Jones tube conjunctivodacryocystorhinostomy may be required for complete canalicular obliteration.<br><br>Lacrimal gland destruction (A) causes dry eye not NLD obstruction. Tumour recurrence (B) requires imaging exclusion. Chemotherapy canalicular fibrosis (C) affects the canaliculi not the NLD specifically. Conjunctival scarring (E) blocks the puncta not the NLD.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old presents with primary acquired NLD obstruction. Which investigation most accurately identifies the level of obstruction before surgical planning?",o:["Fluorescein dye disappearance test","Jones primary dye test","Schirmer tear secretion test","Lacrimal syringing and probing","Dacryocystography with contrast"],a:4,e:"Dacryocystography with radio-opaque contrast injected through the canaliculus provides detailed anatomical imaging of the lacrimal drainage system identifying the precise level and extent of obstruction including partial and complete stenoses.<br><br>CT dacryocystography provides additional bony detail. Dacryoscintigraphy assesses functional drainage dynamics. DCG is the gold standard for surgical planning before revision DCR.<br><br>Fluorescein dye disappearance (A) assesses function not anatomy. Jones I test (B) distinguishes partial from complete obstruction. Schirmer test (C) assesses tear secretion. Syringing and probing (D) confirm obstruction but not its precise anatomical level.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old man has undergone three failed DCR procedures for NLD obstruction. Dye disappears from the conjunctival sac normally but the eye still waters. What is the most likely explanation?",o:["NLD obstruction has recurred completely","Surgical failure requiring a fourth DCR","Functional epiphora from lid laxity and lacrimal pump failure","Corneal surface disease causing reflex tearing","Silicone"],a:2,e:"Normal fluorescein dye disappearance with persistent epiphora after patent DCR indicates functional epiphora not anatomical obstruction. Anatomical patency is confirmed by syringing but the lacrimal pump is insufficient to clear tears efficiently.<br><br>Causes include lid laxity, orbicularis weakness, and medial canthal tendon laxity. Bilateral lid laxity repair and medial canthal tightening restore pump function improving tear clearance.<br><br>NLD recurrence (A) would show abnormal dye disappearance. Fourth DCR (B) is inappropriate when dye disappearance is normal. Corneal surface disease (D) causes reflex hypersecretion. Silicone tube erosion (E) is excluded as tubes are removed.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The Jones primary dye test is performed and fluorescein is recovered from the nose. What does this confirm?",o:["Normal lacrimal drainage","Partial NLD obstruction","Complete NLD obstruction","Canalicular obstruction present","Lacrimal"],a:0,e:"A positive Jones I test, where fluorescein is recovered from the nose after instillation into the conjunctival sac, confirms anatomically and functionally normal lacrimal drainage. No obstruction is present in the canaliculi, sac, or NLD.<br><br>If Jones I is negative, syringing is performed to distinguish functional epiphora from anatomical obstruction. Functional epiphora shows normal syringing with negative Jones I due to impaired lacrimal pump.<br><br>Partial obstruction (B) gives negative Jones I but normal syringing. Complete NLD obstruction (C) gives negative Jones I with blocked syringing. Canalicular obstruction (D) gives negative Jones I with reflux on syringing. Lacrimal hypersecretion (E) causes epiphora not a positive Jones I finding.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old woman presents with bilateral epiphora worse in cold wind. Syringing is normal bilaterally. Schirmer test shows 25 mm wetting. What is the most likely diagnosis?",o:["Bilateral NLD obstruction","Bilateral canalicular stenosis","Keratoconjunctivitis sicca with reflex hypersecretion","Bilateral dacryocystitis","Bilateral functional epiphora from lid laxity"],a:4,e:"Bilateral epiphora with normal syringing and normal tear production indicates functional epiphora. Cold wind is a physiological stimulus that triggers reflex tearing exceeding the drainage capacity when the lacrimal pump is impaired from lid laxity or orbicularis weakness.<br><br>Bilateral medial canthal tendon tightening and lower lid ectropion repair restore the pump mechanism. The diagnosis is functional lacrimal drainage failure.<br><br>Bilateral NLD obstruction (A) would show abnormal syringing. Bilateral canalicular stenosis (B) shows reflux on syringing. Keratoconjunctivitis sicca (C) causes dry eye with low Schirmer values. Bilateral dacryocystitis (D) shows mucopurulent regurgitation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old woman presents with NLD obstruction secondary to nasal polyps. Which underlying condition most commonly causes nasal polyposis leading to NLD obstruction?",o:["Rhinoscleroma granulomatous infection","Aspergillus invasive sinusitis","Chronic allergic rhinosinusitis","Wegener granulomatosis nasal involvement","Inverted papilloma of the nose"],a:2,e:"Chronic allergic rhinosinusitis is the most common cause of nasal polyposis. Nasal polyps prolapsing into the inferior meatus compress and obstruct the NLD as it opens through the valve of Hasner.<br><br>Polypectomy combined with treatment of the underlying allergy may restore NLD patency. DCR is required for established fibrotic NLD obstruction despite polyp removal.<br><br>Rhinoscleroma (A) is a specific granulomatous infection. Aspergillus sinusitis (B) causes invasive fungal disease. Wegener granulomatosis (D) causes granulomatous NLD disease. Inverted papilloma (E) is rare and not a common bilateral NLD cause.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old woman presents with NLD obstruction and facial pain after a road traffic accident with nasoethmoid fracture. CT shows bony fragments in the lacrimal fossa. What is the management?",o:["Topical antibiotic drops only","DCR surgery alone without fracture repair","Conservative management with observation for six months","Open reduction of nasoethmoid fracture with simultaneous DCR and lacrimal intubation","Endoscopic sinus surgery alone"],a:3,e:"Nasoethmoid fractures involving the lacrimal fossa require open reduction with bony fragment repositioning combined with DCR and silicone tube intubation to restore the lacrimal drainage pathway and prevent permanent NLD obstruction.<br><br>Simultaneous repair is optimal as scarring from delayed repair worsens surgical outcomes. Combined maxillofacial and oculoplastic surgical approach achieves the best functional and cosmetic result.<br><br>Topical antibiotics (A) treat infection but not the mechanical obstruction. DCR alone (B) without fracture reduction is insufficient. Conservative observation (C) risks permanent fibrotic obstruction. Endoscopic sinus surgery alone (E) does not address the lacrimal drainage anatomy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old man presents with epiphora and is found to have NLD obstruction on syringing. He also has bilateral inferior turbinate hypertrophy. Which investigation confirms the functional success of DCR before and after surgery?",o:["Hertel exophthalmometry","Schirmer test","Slit-lamp biomicroscopy","Corneal topography","Dacryoscintigraphy with technetium-99m"],a:4,e:"Dacryoscintigraphy uses technetium-99m sodium pertechnetate drops instilled into the conjunctival sac and imaged with a gamma camera. It quantifies functional lacrimal drainage before and after DCR, showing transit time and drainage efficiency.<br><br>It distinguishes anatomical obstruction from functional failure and identifies partial obstructions not detected by syringing. It is particularly valuable for post-DCR assessment of functional drainage.<br><br>Hertel exophthalmometry (A) measures proptosis. Schirmer test (B) assesses tear secretion. Slit-lamp biomicroscopy (C) assesses the anterior segment. Corneal topography (D) maps corneal curvature. None of these assess lacrimal drainage dynamics.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 50-year-old presents with NLD obstruction and is found on DCG to have a complete block at the junction of the lacrimal sac and NLD. Which DCR technique specifically addresses this level of obstruction?",o:["Standard external or endonasal DCR","Lacrimal sac marsupialization","Canaliculodacryocystorhinostomy","Conjunctivodacryocystorhinostomy with Jones tube","Probing alone"],a:0,e:"Complete obstruction at the sac-NLD junction is the classic indication for standard external or endonasal DCR. The rhinostomy connects the lacrimal sac above the obstruction directly to the nasal cavity bypassing the blocked NLD entirely.<br><br>The level of obstruction determines the surgical approach. Sac-NLD junction obstruction is the most common site and the most straightforward for standard DCR with excellent success rates.<br><br>Canaliculodacryocystorhinostomy (C) is for combined canalicular and NLD obstruction. Lacrimal sac marsupialization (B) is for specific lacrimal sac pathology. Jones tube CDCR (D) is for complete canalicular obliteration. Probing alone (E) is for congenital membranous obstruction in children.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old woman with granulomatosis with polyangiitis presents with bilateral NLD obstruction. She is on systemic cyclophosphamide. What specific lacrimal surgical complication is elevated in this patient?",o:["Haemorrhage from anticoagulation","Corneal perforation during surgery","Increased DCR failure rate from ongoing mucosal inflammation and fibrosis","Silicone tube migration postoperatively","Anaesthetic"],a:2,e:"GPA causes granulomatous NLD obstruction with ongoing mucosal inflammation even during systemic immunosuppression. DCR failure rates are significantly higher than primary NLD obstruction because ongoing fibrosis closes the rhinostomy despite surgical creation.<br><br>Mitomycin C application intraoperatively and prolonged silicone tube intubation improve success rates. Multidisciplinary management coordinating systemic disease control with surgical timing optimises outcomes.<br><br>Haemorrhage (A) is not specifically elevated in GPA patients on cyclophosphamide alone. Corneal perforation (B) is unrelated. Silicone tube migration (D) is a general complication. Anaesthetic complications (E) are not specific to GPA.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old woman presents with epiphora and a history of previous nasal fracture. On syringing, fluid passes but with high pressure. DCG shows narrowing at the mid-NLD level. What is the treatment?",o:["Dacryocystorhinostomy bypassing the stenosis","Balloon dacryocystoplasty to dilate the stenosis","Silicone tube intubation alone","Repeated NLD probing","Topical steroid drops reducing NLD"],a:1,e:"Balloon dacryocystoplasty involves passing a balloon catheter through the nasolacrimal duct under fluoroscopic guidance and inflating it to dilate the stenotic segment. It is most appropriate for partial NLD obstruction or post-traumatic NLD stenosis.<br><br>Success rates are lower than DCR for complete obstruction. It is preferred in patients unfit for surgery or with partial stenosis. Silicone tube intubation follows balloon dilation to maintain patency.<br><br>DCR (A) is appropriate for complete obstruction. Silicone tube intubation alone (C) does not dilate a stenotic segment. Repeated probing (D) is for congenital obstruction in children. Topical steroids (E) do not dilate fibrotic stenosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old woman with Stevens-Johnson syndrome has both canaliculi completely obliterated with symblepharal bands closing the puncta. What surgical procedure addresses this complete lacrimal obstruction?",o:["Standard external DCR surgery","Endonasal DCR with silicone intubation","Probing and dilation of canaliculi","Silicone tube intubation through canaliculi","Conjunctivodacryocystorhinostomy with"],a:4,e:"Complete canalicular obliteration from Stevens-Johnson syndrome requires conjunctivodacryocystorhinostomy, creating an entirely new drainage channel directly from the conjunctival sac to the nasal cavity via a permanently placed Pyrex Jones tube.<br><br>Jones tube CDCR bypasses the completely obliterated canalicular system. Tube maintenance is lifelong. Complications include migration, extrusion, and granuloma formation.<br><br>Standard external DCR (A) and endonasal DCR (B) require patent canaliculi. Probing (C) is impossible through obliterated canaliculi. Silicone tube intubation (D) requires canalicular patency for tube passage.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old man presents with right epiphora. Dye disappearance test shows slow disappearance at five minutes bilaterally. Syringing is normal bilaterally. What is the most likely diagnosis?",o:["Bilateral NLD obstruction","Bilateral canalicular stenosis","Bilateral lacrimal sac mucocele","Bilateral functional lacrimal drainage failure","Bilateral dacryocystitis"],a:3,e:"Slow dye disappearance with normal syringing bilaterally confirms functional lacrimal drainage failure. Anatomical patency is confirmed by syringing but the lacrimal pump is insufficient to clear tears efficiently from the conjunctival sac.<br><br>Causes include lid laxity, orbicularis weakness, and medial canthal tendon laxity. Bilateral lid laxity repair and medial canthal tightening restore pump function improving tear clearance.<br><br>Bilateral NLD obstruction (A) and canalicular stenosis (B) show abnormal syringing. Bilateral lacrimal sac mucocele (C) shows mucopurulent regurgitation. Bilateral dacryocystitis (E) shows mucopurulent reflux on syringing.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 2-year-old child with Down syndrome presents with persistent bilateral NLD obstruction unresponsive to probing twice. What is the next management step?",o:["Observe until five years of age","Topical antibiotic drops indefinitely","External DCR bilaterally","Silicone tube intubation alone","Bilateral silicone tube intubation with or without turbinate"],a:4,e:"After two failed probings in a child with persistent NLD obstruction, silicone tube bicanalicular intubation is the next step. Inferior turbinate infracture may be added to create more space at the valve of Hasner in patients with narrow nasal passages, particularly in Down syndrome.<br><br>Tubes are left for three to six months then removed. DCR is reserved for children with complete failure of silicone tube intubation.<br><br>Observation until five years (A) risks chronic infection and corneal complications. Indefinite topical antibiotics (B) do not resolve obstruction. External DCR (C) is premature after only two failed probings. Silicone tube intubation alone without infracture (D) is incomplete for this high-risk child.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old man undergoes external DCR. On postoperative day one he develops epistaxis. What is the most appropriate immediate management?",o:["Return to theatre for emergency surgery","Intravenous antibiotics and observation","Nasal packing with anterior epistaxis pack and head elevation","Topical vasoconstrictors to the eye only","Oral tranexamic"],a:2,e:"Postoperative epistaxis after DCR is managed conservatively with anterior nasal packing, head elevation, ice application, and topical vasoconstrictors. Most post-DCR bleeds are from the nasal mucosal flaps and resolve with conservative measures.<br><br>Surgical re-exploration is rarely required. Hypertension must be controlled. Bilateral nasal packing is avoided to prevent airway compromise. Most bleeds settle within 24 to 48 hours.<br><br>Emergency theatre (A) is only for uncontrolled arterial haemorrhage. Intravenous antibiotics and observation (B) do not address haemorrhage. Topical eye vasoconstrictors (D) have no effect on nasal bleeding. Oral tranexamic acid alone (E) is insufficient for active epistaxis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old woman undergoes endonasal DCR with mitomycin C application. What is the role of mitomycin C in DCR surgery?",o:["Antibiotic preventing postoperative infection","Anaesthetic reducing nasal mucosal sensation","Vasoconstrictor reducing intraoperative bleeding","Antifibrinolytic preventing haematoma formation","Antimetabolite reducing rhinostomy fibrosis"],a:4,e:"Mitomycin C is an antimetabolite that inhibits fibroblast proliferation and collagen synthesis at the rhinostomy site. Application to the mucosal edges reduces fibrotic closure improving long-term patency rates particularly in revision DCR cases.<br><br>Concentration of 0.2 to 0.4 mg/ml applied for two to three minutes on a surgical sponge is the standard protocol. It is most beneficial in high-risk cases with scarred tissue.<br><br>Antibiotic (A), anaesthetic (B), vasoconstrictor (C), and antifibrinolytic (D) are all incorrect mechanisms for mitomycin C in DCR surgery.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old presents with NLD obstruction and is found to have a maxillary sinus carcinoma on CT invading the NLD canal from below. What is the management?",o:["DCR surgery to bypass the obstruction","Topical antibiotics and surveillance","Radiotherapy to the maxillary sinus only","Silicone tube intubation to maintain NLD patency","Oncological referral for"],a:4,e:"NLD obstruction from maxillary sinus carcinoma is secondary to malignant invasion of the NLD canal. The priority is oncological management of the primary malignancy including radical surgical resection and radiotherapy.<br><br>DCR in the presence of malignancy is inappropriate and potentially spreads disease. Staging imaging with CT and MRI defines the extent of the tumour before treatment planning.<br><br>DCR (A) is contraindicated in malignant NLD obstruction. Topical antibiotics and surveillance (B) are inappropriate for malignancy. Radiotherapy alone (C) is inadequate staging and treatment. Silicone intubation (D) does not address the malignant cause.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old woman presents with watering eye. On examination there is no mucopurulent regurgitation. The fluorescein dye disappearance test shows dye still present in the conjunctival sac at five minutes. Syringing shows fluid passing easily. What is the next investigation?",o:["Dacryocystography","Dacryoscintigraphy","CT orbits","B-scan orbital ultrasound","MRI lacrimal system"],a:1,e:"Normal syringing with abnormal fluorescein dye disappearance test indicates functional lacrimal drainage failure rather than anatomical obstruction. Dacryoscintigraphy quantifies the functional drainage dynamics showing delayed transit time and confirming lacrimal pump insufficiency.<br><br>Scintigraphy guides management toward functional interventions such as lid laxity repair rather than DCR which would not resolve functional epiphora.<br><br>Dacryocystography (A) is for anatomical obstruction mapping but shows normal anatomy here. CT orbits (C) is for orbital pathology. B-scan ultrasound (D) assesses posterior orbital anatomy. MRI lacrimal system (E) is for detailed soft tissue anatomy of structural disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 12-year-old girl presents with persistent unilateral NLD obstruction. She has had probing twice and one silicone tube intubation without resolution. What is the next surgical option?",o:["Fourth probing under general anaesthesia","Long-term topical antibiotics","Conservative observation until adulthood","Dacryocystorhinostomy","Jones tube conjunctivodacryocystorhinostomy"],a:3,e:"After failed probing and silicone tube intubation in a child, DCR is the appropriate next surgical step. Endonasal DCR in older children has excellent success rates and avoids an external scar.<br><br>DCR success rates in children are slightly lower than in adults due to the more reactive mucosal healing. Mitomycin C application improves success rates in paediatric DCR.<br><br>Fourth probing (A) has very low success rates after two failed probings and a failed tube. Long-term antibiotics (B) manage infection but do not relieve obstruction. Observation until adulthood (C) risks corneal and conjunctival complications. Jones tube CDCR (E) is for complete canalicular obliteration not NLD obstruction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old woman asks how long silicone tubes will remain after DCR surgery. What is the standard duration for silicone tube intubation after DCR?",o:["Three to six months then removed","One month maximum duration","Two weeks then removed at clinic","One year minimum before removal","Permanent lifetime indwelling tubes"],a:0,e:"Silicone bicanalicular intubation tubes stent the rhinostomy during healing reducing fibrotic closure. Standard duration is three to six months after which tubes are removed in clinic by cutting the nasal loop and withdrawing through the canaliculi.<br><br>Early removal before three months risks premature rhinostomy closure. Prolonged intubation beyond six months increases risks of canalicular erosion, punctal cheese-wiring, and granuloma formation.<br><br>Two weeks (C) and one month (B) are too short. One year minimum (D) risks punctal and canalicular complications. Permanent tubes (E) describes Jones tubes not standard DCR silicone intubation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old man presents with bilateral nasolacrimal duct obstruction and a diagnosis of primary amyloidosis. How does amyloid cause NLD obstruction?",o:["Amyloid deposits compress the NLD from adjacent orbital involvement","Amyloid fibril deposition within the NLD wall causing luminal stenosis","Amyloid causes secondary infection obliterating the NLD lumen","Amyloid causes nasal polyposis obstructing the valve of Hasner","Amyloid deposits in the conjunctiva block the puncta"],a:1,e:"Primary amyloidosis deposits amyloid fibrils within the lacrimal drainage system wall causing progressive luminal stenosis. The NLD epithelium is replaced by amyloid deposits causing functional and anatomical obstruction.<br><br>DCR removes the obstructed segment and creates a new drainage channel. Histology of the lacrimal sac wall confirms amyloid deposits with Congo red staining showing apple-green birefringence under polarised light.<br><br>Orbital compression (A) causes proptosis not NLD obstruction. Secondary infection (C) is a consequence not cause. Nasal polyposis (D) is not an amyloid mechanism. Conjunctival deposits (E) cause conjunctival stiffness not punctal obstruction.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 50-year-old woman presents with unilateral epiphora. The Jones primary dye test is negative. On irrigation, fluid passes but only with moderate pressure and there is no regurgitation. Where is the likely obstruction?",o:["Complete NLD obstruction with dilated sac","Canalicular obstruction at the common canaliculus","Partial NLD obstruction or functional stenosis","Punctal stenosis preventing probe entry","Functional"],a:2,e:"Negative Jones I test with fluid passing on irrigation at moderate pressure indicates partial NLD obstruction rather than complete obstruction. The NLD lumen is narrowed but not completely blocked allowing fluid passage under pressure but not normal tear flow.<br><br>Balloon dacryocystoplasty or DCR with silicone tube intubation treats partial NLD obstruction. Management depends on the degree of obstruction and associated symptoms.<br><br>Complete NLD obstruction (A) blocks irrigation entirely. Canalicular obstruction (B) shows reflux through the opposite punctum. Punctal stenosis (D) prevents probe entry. Functional pump failure (E) shows normal irrigation without pressure.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old woman presents with epiphora and NLD obstruction secondary to chronic sinusitis. What is the mechanism of sinusitis causing NLD obstruction?",o:["Sinusitis causes dry eye which overfills the drainage system","Sinusitis causes NLD obstruction through ascending infection and mucosal oedema at the valve of Hasner","Sinusitis causes reflex lacrimation from trigeminal stimulation only","Sinusitis damages the lacrimal gland causing hypersecretion","Sinusitis causes bony NLD canal erosion"],a:1,e:"Chronic sinusitis causes mucosal oedema and inflammation in the inferior meatus where the NLD opens through the valve of Hasner. Ascending infection and fibrosis progressively stenose the NLD opening causing obstruction and epiphora.<br><br>Treating the underlying sinusitis and DCR for established obstruction are required. Functional endoscopic sinus surgery combined with endonasal DCR is an efficient combined approach.<br><br>Dry eye overfilling (A) is not the mechanism. Reflex lacrimation only (C) is insufficient to cause obstruction. Lacrimal gland damage (D) does not cause NLD obstruction. Bony canal erosion (E) requires aggressive infection or malignancy not typical sinusitis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old woman undergoes endonasal DCR. Postoperatively she develops a granuloma at the common canalicular opening into the lacrimal sac causing recurrent epiphora three months later. What is the treatment?",o:["Topical steroid drops indefinitely","Systemic steroids for three months","Excision of the granuloma with canalicular dilation and repeat silicone intubation","Repeat external DCR immediately","Jones tube"],a:2,e:"Canalicular granuloma at the common canalicular opening is a recognised complication of silicone tube intubation causing obstruction and epiphora. Treatment involves careful excision of the granuloma under magnification, dilation of the canaliculus, and replacement of silicone intubation tubes to maintain patency during healing.<br><br>Office-based or minor theatre excision under local anaesthesia is usually sufficient. Complete excision prevents recurrence.<br><br>Topical steroids (A) do not dissolve a granuloma. Systemic steroids (B) are insufficient for a physical obstruction. Repeat DCR (D) is premature without addressing the granuloma. Jones tube (E) is for complete canalicular obliteration not granuloma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old man with primary acquired NLD obstruction has the Jones secondary dye test performed. Fluorescein is recovered from the nose after saline irrigation. What does this result indicate?",o:["Anatomically and functionally normal drainage","Complete NLD obstruction with no drainage","Functional epiphora with intact anatomy","Partial NLD obstruction with distal stenosis","Common canalicular"],a:3,e:"A positive Jones II test where fluorescein is recovered after irrigation despite a negative Jones I indicates that the canaliculi and lacrimal sac are patent allowing dye entry but the NLD has partial obstruction preventing spontaneous drainage. Irrigation forces dye through the stenotic NLD.<br><br>This confirms partial NLD obstruction requiring surgical intervention. DCR creates a new rhinostomy bypassing the stenotic NLD segment.<br><br>Normal drainage (A) shows positive Jones I. Complete obstruction (B) prevents fluorescein recovery even with irrigation. Functional epiphora (C) shows positive Jones I. Common canalicular obstruction (E) shows reflux through the opposite canaliculus.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old woman presents with bilateral NLD obstruction and recurrent dacryocystitis. She is pregnant at 20 weeks gestation. What is the appropriate management?",o:["Immediate bilateral DCR under general anaesthesia","Bilateral probing under local anaesthetic immediately","Endonasal DCR in the second trimester","Bilateral DCR under spinal anaesthesia","Conservative management with antibiotics and massage until delivery then"],a:4,e:"DCR surgery during pregnancy carries anaesthetic risks to the foetus. Conservative management with topical antibiotics for secondary infection, warm compresses, and lacrimal sac massage controls symptoms until delivery. DCR is planned electively postpartum.<br><br>Acute dacryocystitis abscess formation during pregnancy may require incision and drainage under local anaesthesia. Systemic antibiotics safe in pregnancy manage acute infections.<br><br>Immediate bilateral DCR under general anaesthesia (A) carries unnecessary foetal risk. Bilateral probing (B) does not resolve NLD obstruction in adults. Endonasal DCR in second trimester (C) carries anaesthetic risks. Spinal anaesthesia DCR (D) is not appropriate for bilateral orbital surgery.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old man presents with right epiphora following right nasal radiotherapy five years ago. Syringing shows complete right NLD obstruction. What specific factor makes DCR most challenging in this patient?",o:["Elderly age reducing surgical tolerance","Anticoagulation from cardiac disease","Bilateral disease requiring simultaneous repair","Nasal polyps obstructing the surgical field","Radiation fibrosis"],a:4,e:"Radiation-induced NLD obstruction creates densely fibrotic tissue with impaired vascularity and wound healing capacity. DCR success rates are significantly lower than in primary NLD obstruction because the rhinostomy closes rapidly from fibrotic tissue contraction.<br><br>Prolonged silicone tube intubation for 12 months, intraoperative mitomycin C, and larger osteotomy size improve outcomes. Jones tube CDCR is considered if multiple DCR attempts fail.<br><br>Elderly age (A) is not specifically challenging. Anticoagulation (B) affects bleeding not healing. Bilateral disease (C) is not the issue here. Nasal polyps (D) are not related to radiation NLD obstruction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
];